    "summary": "Main objection to \"constitutive nature\": too heavy for running text",
    "content": "My objection is practical, not philosophical. \"Constitutive nature\" is accurate -- I do not dispute the chinese-phil-expert's analysis of the term's semantic fit. The problem is that it is six syllables and two words in a passage where 德 appears densely and repeatedly.\n\nLook at the 道德仁义礼 passage. In a single paragraph the author moves through 德 multiple times in close succession -- \"人人皆而有之的东西...便是德,\" \"凡事诸物皆有其德,\" \"所有的德合起来...归纳抽象出道.\" In English this becomes: \"...this is the constitutive nature,\" \"everything has its constitutive nature,\" \"all constitutive natures together are abstracted into...\" The phrase accumulates weight with each repetition. \"Character\" does the same work in two syllables: \"this is the character,\" \"everything has its character,\" \"all characters together...\"\n\nIf the team prefers \"constitutive nature\" for its precision, I would accept it -- but I would suggest the translator be given license to shorten to \"nature\" after the first few occurrences in dense passages, with \"constitutive\" reintroduced only when the constructivist dimension needs re-emphasis. This is a compromise I could live with."
  }
